result.execSummary:
The defendant Jose Manuel Hernandez was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Misappropriate ID Info - Obtain Money, a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.201(2)(a).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

2:35 pm  Court in session.  Case called.  Appearances given.  
Atty Diane M. Donohoo appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  
Defendant Jose Manuel Hernandez in court with Atty Aneeq Ahmad.  
Matter is before the Court on defendant's Motion to Amend the Criminal Complaint.  
Attorney Donohoo states that they realized the probable cause section was a little light on dates so they have filed an Amended Complaint.   
Attorney Ahmad objects to the amended criminal complaint for same reasons set forth in his Motion.  
Argument by Attorney Donohoo.  Response by Attorney Ahmad.  
Continued discussion between Court and Attorneys.  
Court believes the ongoing receipt of money based upon the use of a someone else's personal identification document or information can be charged as the State did in the Amended Criminal Complaint.  Court denies the motion.  
Attorney Ahmad advises that Mr. Hernandez will waive his right to a preliminary hearing.  
Court has colloquy with Mr. Hernandez concerning his waiver of preliminary hearing.  
Court finds waiver to have been made knowingly, voluntarily and intelligently.  Court binds the defendant over.
